WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.698
again is illustrated here.

00:03.159 --> 00:05.024
As we said, it's pretty simple.

00:05.465 --> 00:12.083
First, so step one, step one, train the teacher model with labeled data, as you would.

00:13.345 --> 00:17.994
Step two, you infer the pseudo labels on unlabeled data.

00:18.515 --> 00:32.822
Step three, you make a student, sorry, we'll step three over here, train an equal or larger student model with combined data and noise injected.

00:32.802 --> 00:40.600
So they use the original labeled data here and the pseudo labeled data right here in order to train the student.

00:40.881 --> 00:46.294
But still, the student doesn't have more information, more label information than the teacher had.

00:46.434 --> 00:49.782
It simply has this teacher labeled

00:49.762 --> 01:12.343
teacher labeled unlabeled data also to train on now the crucial part here is well first of all that the student can be larger and second of all that there can be noise and the noise comes in three different forms so first of all you use data augmentation which we've already seen this is sort of like random cropping or

01:12.323 --> 01:14.627
mild rotations, color, jitter, whatever.

01:14.687 --> 01:19.735
They use a random augment here, which is a specific technique to apply these augmentations.

01:20.496 --> 01:32.475
They use drop out, which is a fairly old technique where you, in the student model that you train, you randomly drop out connections, which makes it more robust and more generalizing.

01:32.455 --> 01:34.338
And then you also use stochastic depth.

01:34.398 --> 01:48.580
Now stochastic depth is a technique when you train a model, what you'll do during training, instead of always passing your data forward through the layers like this, you use some sort of a dropout but with entire layers.

01:49.001 --> 01:57.214
So what you'll do is you'll pass your data forward and then randomly you'll skip a layer and then pass it forward again.

01:57.194 --> 02:15.473
Now, these might seem weird first because, yeah, it might seem weird, but if you know that most models, especially computer vision models nowadays, are residual networks, which means that their layers look like, so you have the input

02:15.453 --> 02:27.252
You have some computation and then you have the output and then there is already a residual connection that basically adds the original signal together to the result of the computation.

02:27.813 --> 02:42.456
So all you do in this stochastic layer dropout or this stochastic depth right here is you basically disable this connection right here and all the signal has to flow through here.

02:42.436 --> 02:49.629
If you read the original ResNet paper, they make it pretty clear why the residual connection is a good idea.

02:50.190 --> 03:01.812
Basically, they say these computations here, if you have a very deep network, each layer only has to basically do a little bit of computation that

03:01.792 --> 03:07.261
that can be bypassed fairly efficiently for a lot of data points.

03:07.602 --> 03:09.866
So it's not that hurtful to bypass a layer.

03:10.407 --> 03:19.783
And in this case, they actually use it to just bypass some of these small computations and inject some more robustness into the student model.

03:19.763 --> 03:28.352
So with these three strategies to bring noise into the training process, one is on the data and two is on the student model itself.

03:29.032 --> 03:41.145
They train the student model and then fourth, and this is what we didn't have before, fourth, or maybe we put four here, make the student a new teacher.

03:41.185 --> 03:42.386
So now you can iterate.

03:42.726 --> 03:48.572
You can use the student model that you just trained to again label the unlabeled data.

03:48.552 --> 03:56.392
And then you can use another student model again under the influence of noise to train from that student model and so on.

03:56.412 --> 04:04.553
And you can go on and they do up to like three iterations of this where they always take the new the student as the new teacher.

04:04.533 --> 04:10.141
and then use a new student model to train from that teacher.

04:10.963 --> 04:13.787
And they get better and better as they do this.

04:13.807 --> 04:19.816
Of course, there's like a diminishing returns, but it's pretty impressive that this even works, right?

04:20.316 --> 04:24.923
The new students in fact aren't even larger than the old students.

04:24.963 --> 04:29.931
It's just that the students are larger than the original teacher model in most of these cases.

04:30.692 --> 04:32.835
So here's the algorithm written down.

04:32.815 --> 04:39.226
You'll require labeled images right here and unlabeled images, which are the ones with the tilde.

04:40.488 --> 04:45.136
So first you learn the teacher model, which minimizes the cross entropy on labeled images.

04:45.337 --> 04:48.883
This we already know this, right?

04:48.863 --> 04:56.076
This is the label, this is the image according to the label, and you train the teacher model, which is this thing here.

04:56.317 --> 04:57.819
And you can see here, noise.

04:58.160 --> 05:04.071
So already in the teacher training process, you want to introduce this noise, you want to introduce these data augmentations.

05:04.111 --> 05:10.703
These are, as I said, these are standard techniques to make models more robust and therefore more generalizable.

05:10.683 --> 05:33.552
Yeah, we know from these, from these self-supervised papers that these augmentations are very powerful and the way you design them, basically, if you, one of these augmentations is a random crop, which means if you have an image, you randomly crop out like part of that image and then that's your training sample and not the entire thing.

05:33.532 --> 05:43.083
So by doing this, you basically teaching the model to ignore the exact location and scale of things on an image.

05:43.443 --> 05:50.932
And you can do this because you as a human know that, you know, I can zoom in, I can zoom out into something and it won't change what's on the picture.

05:51.673 --> 05:58.881
And so that's, you use these augmentations to kind of heuristically tell the model what it should be invariant to.

05:58.861 --> 06:07.615
And that is a very powerful technique to regularize, basically, to robustify these deep methods.

06:08.697 --> 06:09.879
And this is used the same here.

06:09.999 --> 06:14.727
So already in the teacher model, we train with this noise and then

06:16.208 --> 06:25.001
Step two, use a normal IE not noise teacher model to generate soft or hard pseudo labels for the clean IE not distorted unlabeled images.

06:25.481 --> 06:26.383
And this is important.

06:26.403 --> 06:40.343
They stress this here that when you label the unlabeled images, you want to use the model that is without the noise and you do it on the not distorted unlabeled images.

06:40.323 --> 06:48.458
So when you infer the labels, it's very important that you have clean accurate labels without any sort of noise in them.

06:48.518 --> 06:52.726
So label noise is not something that they have found to help in this case.

06:53.227 --> 06:56.172
So not label noise on the teacher, that is.

06:57.130 --> 07:04.778
So you can see right here on the unlabeled images, we'll use that teacher model without the noise to infer the labels.

07:04.798 --> 07:09.582
Now, they say these can be hard model, hard labels or soft labels.

07:10.063 --> 07:10.824
So what does that mean?

07:11.644 --> 07:20.513
If we generate hard pseudo labels, that means that the Y here is simply going to be either zero or one or two or three and so on.

07:20.613 --> 07:25.298
So just the index of the class, whichever class is most likely, that's going to be our label.

07:25.278 --> 07:29.102
This is exactly how the supervised data sets come, right?

07:29.523 --> 07:32.566
So this is what you'll think first when you see that.

07:32.766 --> 07:37.792
However, soft pseudo labels means that the y will be a distribution.

07:37.852 --> 07:52.669
So instead of being of class zero, it will be sort of, let's say, 90% of class zero, but also 5% class one and 5% class two, right?

07:52.649 --> 07:57.902
So you'll output the distribution instead of the just the label.

07:58.484 --> 08:04.779
And they have found that the soft pseudo labels work slightly, slightly better than the hard pseudo labels.

08:06.844 --> 08:07.907
Okay, thanks.

08:11.482 --> 08:18.215
So they use the soft pseudo labels here because they work slightly better, but you can do it with hard or soft labels.

08:18.275 --> 08:26.892
The important thing is that you use the teacher to generate as accurate as possible labels for your unlabeled data.

08:26.872 --> 08:39.396
Then third, we've already seen this, learn an equal or larger student model, which minimizes the cross entropy loss on labeled images and unlabeled images with noise added to the student model.

08:40.017 --> 08:45.488
So as you can see, labeled images and unlabeled images, so we're in this semi

08:45.468 --> 08:56.229
semi-supervised learning setting right now you take in both together with noise and noise here is in bold which means they stress it again this is important.

08:56.891 --> 09:00.217
So you can see that the loss is composed of two different things.

09:00.778 --> 09:05.147
These are the true images of your original model.

09:05.127 --> 09:10.834
And you use that, and this means you noise the student model.

09:11.295 --> 09:14.419
And that noise can be on the data or in the model itself.

09:15.180 --> 09:21.928
And here, also the unlabeled images that you have labeled with the teacher, you do the exact same thing.

09:22.449 --> 09:24.632
So you train on both of these data sets.

09:25.573 --> 09:31.320
And step four is if you want to do iterative training, use the student as a teacher and go back to step two.

09:33.629 --> 09:37.039
Now they have some more tricks when they do this iterative training.

09:37.460 --> 09:41.912
They also up the batch size during the iterative training and so on.

09:41.932 --> 09:48.972
So they do a lot of things to make the student learn something more, something better than the teacher.

09:48.952 --> 10:09.762
And I think the whole paper, it doesn't state it explicitly, but I think the whole paper, everything they do here is to kind of force or allow the student to become better than the teacher by giving more noise, by making the student larger, by making the batch size for the student larger, and so on.

10:09.742 --> 10:19.498
So you want to sort of inject as much invariance as you can, and that will make the student learn more.

